This continuation of metre is also extended to the final syllables of verses, so that some lines, which appear to be hypermetrical‚ run into the following line, the two lines being treated as one, and the last foot of the first line having therefore

The same continuation occurs in some cases when the first syllable of a line is connected by Synaloepha with the last syllable of the preceding line; and in many instances this continuation of metre removes some of the irregularities which annoy critics under the shape of shortened syllables. Thus we may in the following lines consider ‘ et’ to coalesce with ‘ modo :’

“Sed epistolam ab eo allatam esse audivi modo, Et ad portitores esse delatam; hanc petam.’' (Phorm. i. 3. 99, 100.)
